The process of growth.

Whether it’s an activity, a class, a relationship, a particular skill, the process of growth can look different for everyone. The way I’ve been able to see it unfold for myself with some things, so far, is:

1. Taking advantage of those sweet moments of inspiration. Whether it’s for 1 or 30 minutes, do the thing for however long when the inspiration swirls in ya. This helps create positive mental associations with the activity.

2. Quantity: doing a lot of the thing. Put aside quaLity temporarily. Starting with the part most enjoyed do A LOT of it everywhere to get comfortable with it, so it can become a part of you; a lifestyle.

4. Reign it in. Change the focus from quanTity to quaLity. 

5. Integrate intentionality. Begin identifying threads of pattern and difference, then see if you can intentionally integrate parts together to create a theme or an intentional offering.

Do I like dark chocolate? 
In 70% or more cocoa: love it. 

Do I like white chocolate? 
LOVE white chocolate.

Do I like salad? 
LOVE salad.

Do I want chocolate to be crumbled up and mixed into my salad? 

Absolutely not by choice. 

Is one flavor better than the other? 
Nope, not to mee. 

If the salad doesn’t like the chocolate mixed in it, is the chocolate not worthy of the salad? Nope, not even relevant, IMO.

How about the other way around? 
Is the salad NOT worthy of the chocolate.
Nope, also not relevant. 

Please stop questioning your worth and value based on another’s ability to gel with your vibe romantically, or otherwise. Stop comparing and being cruel to each other because you fear being unliked. 

If you are here today, it means you are worthy of life. You wouldn’t have been entrusted with it if you weren’t. And just because of this: you are worthy. 

We all come from various cultures, backgrounds, upbringings, preferences, exposure to movies, socioeconomic status, privilege and education that shape the way we perceive the world and our platonic or romantic interests in another, differently. 

Some of us are able to lock in on the value and vision with a wider range of individuals, and others: are more particular. And ALL of that is:  okay. 

Stop people pleasing, be HONEST and direct about where you’re at, and as soon as possible. Anything less, may be toxic. 

From heart to heart, with love.

💡 YOGA TIPS - Stepping up to the top of the mat:

1. Walk up, then step the opposite foot back. 

2. Bend your knees! My friends, if I could change one thing about the start of my yoga journey, it would be to bend my knees more! 

Bending the knees creates more space and flexibility to manipulate the spine and to tuck the tail bone under in order to tilt your hips upwards and thereby creating more room for the opposite leg to step through. 

• Push the floor away with your hands

• Hug the belly in towards the spine and press your back up to the ceiling to hollow out your front body.

3. Make it pretty: curl your toes & try to keep your hands from lifting off the mat.

Happy flowing good time to ya! 😋

💡 YOGA TIPS: CAT / COW POSE

For the first almost 1.5 years of practicing yoga, I did not understand cat and cow pose and actually didn’t prefer it! Now it’s one of my faaaves. 

Here are a few tips that helped me!

COW POSE
(On the inhale)

1. Collapse chest and belly down towards the floor

2. Tilt tail bone up & press forward toward your shoulders to press your chest through your arms (this one was transformational for me).

3. Lift shoulders up and slide them onto your back body.

4. Traction hands back toward your knees.

CAT POSE
(On the exhale)

1. Arch your back and press belly up towards spine

2. Tuck your tail bone under and press your hips slightly forward (toward elbows)

3. Push the floor away with your hands to length through your shoulders

And maybe one day: magical cow! ✨

Feels so good on my spine, enjoy. 😋

Quick tips for learning to handstand! 

Number one tip: Start - even if it’s just for half a minute per day! It’s good for you so let that motivate ya! 

Number two: If you want to learn to handstand, practice handstanding! Integrate strength drills here and there but don’t deny yourself the fun of exploring upside down movement if that is what you want. I was always the girl that tried to sneak handstands in everywhere. (So much so, certain friends were surprised when I didn’t and would prompt me to get on it 😇🤍).

Number three: try the drills in the video 👆🏼This will help you pave the pattern for your body to assume and build up the strength to hold yourself upside down.

Number four (in video): integrate! Try to add little hops and drills everywhere: during workouts, yoga class breaks, vinyasa. Sometimes we can get so focused on achieving one goal (the handstand) that we can forget the bigger picture and the pressure created can actually be counter productive. Try to keep it light: think about how it could add to your life in fun, creative ways and find opportunities to integrate.

Take breaks! Especially if your focus gets too strong. Do something else for a bit and come back fresher and lighter ✨ 

Happy handstanding and please reach out if you have any more questions! Enjoy 🙏🏼💕

While I’d have numerous people and families open up to me and receive the insights as support, the sharing was also not always very well received by the adults in my life. I had to be cautious and learn to choose my words very carefully as to not offend people with the information I had learned. It always surprised me when people weren’t interested in hearing about the concepts that have helped people heal, feel better, more connected and have more FUN with themselves and within their relationships. At one point, beacause of my experience, I decided that when I got older I’d always try to welcome the contributions of young people and make an effort  to use their ideas when I could. When in relationships, I’d love getting feedback from my young friends and even now enjoy listening to the ideas those younger than me have to offer, especially when there is joy and enthusiasm in their presentation.

I’ve learned that it is a decision to open one’s mind and heart to welcome ideas and find ways to creatively integrate feedback. At any moment we can resist the energy and dismiss contributions as “too much” “overly excited” “smart assy” or too ambitious” or we can plug in, get curious and honest about how we actually feel: fears, insecurities and thereby promote connection. When in doubt, I try to opt for curiousity and remember that staying connected and trying new things keeps us youthful. 🤓

A few ideas for letting go of perfectionism and celebrating progress:

Take a break.
Give yourself moments to forget about the task/ project/ endeavor at hand to allow the mind to rest and reset. This helps create space which can lead to more creativity. 

Meet yourself where you’re at. 
Identify and re-identify what is a reasonable starting point for you. Maybe it’s putting in a shorter amount of time or zooming in on a detail. Use your progress as the measurement for where you’re at. 

Support. 
Talk to a friend or counselor about any recurring stuck points. To brainstorm alternative approaches. 

Purpose. 
Come back to the purpose and meaning underlying the intention of the endeavor at hand. (e.g. Is the goal to be perfect or to support and assist others. Will a few mistakes make a difference? There will always be critics, but will a few mistakes deter the effectiveness for the population served. If not, what’s the delay)? 

Perparation.
Take a little extra time to prepare, allowing immersion into specific parts in a more relaxed way can help alleviate the pressure that leads to perfectionism.

Permission to forget. 
Give yourself a reasonable number of tries and then forget about any mistakes made. (If editing your writing is an issue, give yourself only a couple attempts to re-read and edit then forget about it.

Consistency. 
Focus on consistency versus the length of time & temporarily let go of the quality until a reasonable comfort level with the skill is developed. 

Inspiration.
Tune into the sources that maintain and support a growth-mindset, that provide constructive feedback and inspire you to keep going. Avoid the ones that are critical. 

Celebrate progress. 
Define what reasonable progress and celebrating means to you! Then schedule a time to be proud and celebrate the steps forward 🎉

YOGA FOR THE SPINE 

After work spine reset in just 10mins or less. 

1. Cat & cow. In cat: press spine up to the ceiling, relax neck & allow head to hang heavy. In cow: traction your hands back towards your body and press your chest forward from the hips.

2. Balancing table twists. Inhale on the way down & exhale (squeeze belly towards spine) on the way up. 

3. Sphinx. Traction forearms towards the body and press your heart forward. 

4. Oscillating seal. Keep elbows bent and straighten as you gain more flexibility!

5. Ocillating cobra. Roll shoulders back & stretch chest forward at the top. 

6. Ocillating cobra twists. Keep top shoulder reaching back. 

7. Dynamic Cobra. Widen the knees, relax hips & squeeze glutes when pressing your chest forward. 

8. Melting heart. Left up through the tailbone while relaxing chest down towards floor. 

Safe for later & enjoy! 😋
